Wait, no: in Java, when you do System.out.println(someString), it prints the string followed by a newline. So for example, if you do println("5 "), it outputs "5 \n". So each number is printed on its own line, with a space after the number. Then a newline. So the output would be:

n<space>
<newline>
i<space>
<newline>
and so on. But when translated to C, we need to print each number followed by a space and a newline. So for each number, printf("%d \n", num); ? Wait, let's see. The Java code for the first print is System.out.println(n + " "); which is equivalent to printing n followed by a space and then a newline. So in C, that's printf("%d \n", n); Then in the loop, same thing: printf("%d \n", i); But wait, in Java, when you concatenate an integer and a string, like n + " ", that converts n to a string and appends the space. So if n is 6, the first line is "6 " followed by a newline. So in C, we need to print the number, then a space, then a newline. So each printf would be "%d \n" as the format string. So the steps in C:

Read integer n using scanf. Print n followed by a space and a newline. Initialize m as n.

Loop i from n-1 down to 1:

   if m % i == 0, then print i followed by space and newline, set m = i. Now, how to handle the loop. In Java, it's for (int i = n-1; i>0; i--). So in C, same structure: for (int i = n-1; i > 0; i--). So putting it all together:

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int n;
    scanf("%d", &n);
    printf("%d \n", n);
    int m = n;
    for (int i = n - 1; i > 0; i--) {
        if (m % i == 0) {
            printf("%d \n", i);
            m = i;
        }
    }
    return 0;
} Wait, but in C, variables declared in the for loop (like int i) need to be in C99 mode or later.
